    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-28T09:16:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-28T09:16:00-05:00" n="895"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d895">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/268</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Argentina</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SFJ1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stimson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Buenos Aires</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-28T10:00:00-04:16">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 28, 1918, 10 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 2 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your March 24 [<hi rend="italic">23</hi>], 2 [<hi rend="italic">7</hi>] p.m. I
                    saw the Minister of Foreign Affairs this afternoon and took up with him in
                    conversation the matter of the status in Argentine ports of the Dutch ships now
                    taken over by United States, according to instructions conveyed to me in the
                    telegram above referred to.</p>
                <p>The Minister of Foreign Affairs assured me definitely that when such vessels
                    arrive in Argentine ports they will be considered as being the property of the
                    United States, as national vessels, and that <pb facs="0960" n="1794"
                        xml:id="pg_1794"/> the Argentine Government will neither make nor permit to
                    be made any inquiry as to their former ownership; that since this is the
                    attitude of the Government the courts in this country must adopt the same
                    attitude in the event of any attempt to attach them by legal means. To confirm
                    this promise the Minister informed me that he would address a note to me on this
                    question reiterating these assurances.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SFJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
